.TH NETFYR\-EXAMPLES 7 "" "" "Miscellaneous Information Manual"
.SH NAME
netfyr\-examples \- configuration examples for netfyr
.SH DESCRIPTION
This page shows annotated YAML configuration examples for common
netfyr scenarios.
Each example can be saved to a file in
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/
and applied with
.BR "netfyr apply" .
.PP
For field and format reference, see
.BR netfyr.yaml (5).
.SH "STATIC IP ON A SINGLE INTERFACE"
Assign a static IPv4 address, default gateway, and custom MTU to
an interface identified by name.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
mtu: 1500
addresses:
  - 10.0.1.50/24
routes:
  - destination: 0.0.0.0/0
    gateway: 10.0.1.1
.fi
.RE
.SH "MULTIPLE INTERFACES IN ONE FILE"
Configure two interfaces in a single file using the multi-document
separator
.BR \-\-\- .
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
mtu: 9000
addresses:
  - 10.0.1.50/24
---
type: ethernet
name: eth1
mtu: 1500
addresses:
  - 192.168.1.10/24
.fi
.RE
.SH "DHCP ON AN INTERFACE"
Acquire an address via DHCPv4.
Requires the netfyr daemon to be running.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: eth0\-dhcp
factory: dhcpv4
selector:
  name: eth0
.fi
.RE
.SH "MIXED STATIC AND DHCP"
Two files in
.IR /etc/netfyr/policies/ :
one for a static management interface, one for a DHCP uplink.
.PP
File:
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/mgmt.yaml
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
addresses:
  - 192.168.100.1/24
.fi
.RE
.PP
File:
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/uplink.yaml
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: uplink\-dhcp
factory: dhcpv4
selector:
  name: eth1
.fi
.RE
.SH "PRIORITY OVERRIDE"
When two policies set the same field on the same interface, the
higher priority wins.
Here the admin override (priority 200) takes precedence over the
baseline (default priority 100).
.PP
File:
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/baseline.yaml
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
mtu: 1500
.fi
.RE
.PP
File:
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/override.yaml
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
kind: policy
name: jumbo\-frames
factory: static
priority: 200
state:
  type: ethernet
  name: eth0
  mtu: 9000
.fi
.RE
.PP
Result: eth0 gets mtu 9000 because priority 200 > 100.
.SH "SELECTING BY DRIVER"
Apply jumbo frames to all interfaces using the ixgbe driver,
regardless of interface name.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
driver: ixgbe
mtu: 9000
.fi
.RE
.SH "DUAL\-STACK (IPv4 + IPv6)"
Assign both an IPv4 and an IPv6 address to a single interface, with a
default gateway for each address family.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
addresses:
  \- 10.0.1.50/24
  \- fd00::1/64
routes:
  \- destination: 0.0.0.0/0
    gateway: 10.0.1.1
  \- destination: ::/0
    gateway: fd00::ffff
.fi
.RE
.SH "ADDRESS LIFETIMES"
Assign an address with finite valid and preferred lifetimes.
This is useful for addresses that should expire automatically, such as
temporary or delegated prefixes.
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
addresses:
  \- 10.0.1.50/24
  \- address: fd00::1/64
    valid_lft: 3600
    preferred_lft: 1800
.fi
.RE
.PP
Plain strings and mappings can be mixed in the same list.
The
.B valid_lft
and
.B preferred_lft
fields are in seconds.
.SH "ROUTE ATTRIBUTES"
Routes can carry additional attributes such as MTU, routing table, and
TOS (Type of Service).
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
addresses:
  \- 10.0.1.50/24
routes:
  \- destination: 10.100.0.0/24
    gateway: 10.0.1.1
    mtu: 1400
  \- destination: 10.200.0.0/24
    gateway: 10.0.1.1
    table: 100
  \- destination: 10.50.0.0/24
    gateway: 10.0.1.1
    tos: 8
.fi
.RE
.PP
The
.B table
field specifies the routing table ID (default is 254, the main table).
The
.B tos
field sets a TOS/DSCP filter (valid range: 0\(en255).
.SH "DRY\-RUN WORKFLOW"
Preview changes before applying them:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr apply \-\-dry\-run /etc/netfyr/policies/
ethernet/eth0:
  mtu: 1500 \-> 9000
.fi
.RE
.PP
If the diff looks correct, apply for real:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr apply /etc/netfyr/policies/
.fi
.RE
.SH "INVESTIGATING CHANGES WITH HISTORY"
List recent state changes from the journal:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr history
SEQ  TIMESTAMP             TRIGGER         ENTITIES   OUTCOME        CHANGES
145  2026\-04\-20 15:10:05   external        eth0       observed       ~mtu
144  2026\-04\-20 15:00:00   policy\-apply    eth0       applied (1 ok) ~mtu
.fi
.RE
.PP
Show full details for a specific entry:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr history \-\-show 145
Entry #145 at 2026\-04\-20 15:10:05 UTC
Trigger: external\-change
  Changed entities: eth0
Diff:
  ~ ethernet eth0
      mtu: 9000 \-> 1500
Outcome: observed (no action taken)
.fi
.RE
.PP
Filter by entity and output as JSON for scripting:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr history \-s name=eth0 \-\-since 1h \-o json | jq '.[].trigger'
.fi
.RE
.SH "EXTERNAL CHANGE DETECTION"
The daemon automatically monitors managed interfaces for changes made
by other tools.
To use this feature:
.PP
1. Create a policy for the interface you want to monitor:
.PP
File:
.I /etc/netfyr/policies/eth0.yaml
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
type: ethernet
name: eth0
mtu: 9000
.fi
.RE
.PP
2. Apply the policy and start the daemon:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr apply /etc/netfyr/policies/
$ sudo systemctl start netfyr
.fi
.RE
.PP
3. When an external tool changes the interface, the daemon records it
in the journal:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ ip link set eth0 mtu 1500
$ netfyr history \-n 1
SEQ  TIMESTAMP             TRIGGER    ENTITIES  OUTCOME   CHANGES
146  2026\-04\-20 15:15:00   external   eth0      observed  ~mtu
.fi
.RE
.PP
.B Important:
only interfaces targeted by at least one active policy are monitored.
If you want to track changes to an interface, you must have a policy
for it \(em even a minimal one that only declares the type and name.
See
.BR netfyr\-daemon (8)
for full details on limitations.
.SH "REVERTING TO A PREVIOUS STATE"
After investigating changes with
.BR "netfyr history" ,
revert to a known good state:
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr history \-n 3
SEQ  TIMESTAMP             TRIGGER         ENTITIES   OUTCOME        CHANGES
146  2026\-04\-20 15:15:00   external        eth0       observed       ~mtu
145  2026\-04\-20 15:10:05   policy\-apply    eth0       applied (1 ok) ~mtu
144  2026\-04\-20 15:00:00   policy\-apply    eth0       applied (2 ok) ~mtu, addr(+1)
.fi
.RE
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr revert 145 \-\-dry\-run
Reverting to state from entry #145 (2026\-04\-20 15:10:05 UTC)
Changes that would be applied:
  ~ ethernet eth0
      mtu: 1500 \-> 9000
.fi
.RE
.PP
.RS 4
.nf
$ netfyr revert 145
Reverting to state from entry #145 (2026\-04\-20 15:10:05 UTC)
Applied 1 change (1 entity modified).
.fi
.RE
.PP
In daemon mode, a warning is printed because the active policies are
not changed.
The next reconciliation cycle may re\-apply the current desired state.
